  "text": "Several areas of the brain have been identified as being important in opiate mediation of eating. DAMGO or DPEN injected into the ventral striatum, nucleus accumbens [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , or anteroventromedial striatum stimulated eating in nondeprived animals, although the amount of change varied with the specific area of those structures that was injected [CITATION_3] . Because these regions are also involved in impulse control, they may be the opiate mechanism for overeating [CITATION_4] . The lateral hypothalamus, previously shown to mediate taste preferences, increased consumption of saccharin when injected with DAMGO (363), so that it may also play a role in opiate regulation of eating.",
